00:36.280 --> 00:37.960
And here are your hosts.

00:42.060 --> 00:50.620
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. Science fiction writer George R.R. Martin
recently had his third novel, Fevre Dream, published in hardcover by Poseidon

00:50.620 --> 00:58.360
Press. Fevre Dream is a science fictional historical horror novel which combines
the vampire legend and Mississippi riverboats in the antebellum south. We asked

00:58.360 --> 01:06.580
Martin why he chose to write about a combination of vampires and riverboats. The
vampires came first as I was putting the book together. I had read a fair amount

01:06.580 --> 01:15.700
about vampires. I had read other people's vampire novels as far as Dracula and
some of the other books done recently. And I had wanted to do my own version of

01:15.700 --> 01:26.760
that legend for some time because I had a few ideas about it. But I didn't want
it to be just another Dracula book, just another rehash of the same old legend.

01:26.760 --> 01:35.120
Because we've seen vampire books after vampire books that are essentially just
the same thing spun over and over again. And I think that's a little tiresome.

01:35.860 --> 01:44.460
And at the same time I was going through all these thoughts about vampires was
the period that I was living in Dubuque, Iowa. I taught college there for three

01:44.460 --> 01:53.240
years. And Dubuque, of course, is an old river town. It was once a big steamboat
manufacturing center. And it's still very much imbued with the whole history of

01:53.240 --> 02:05.760
the great era of steam on the Mississippi. So it was during that period while I
was in Dubuque that I got interested in that period of history. I got interested

02:05.760 --> 02:14.380
in the steamboats. I read a fair amount about them. And once I did, the two
things just seemed to come together in my mind. And there's a certain

02:14.380 --> 02:27.040
romanticism, I think, a dark romanticism that clings to both the old steamboats
and vampires. They're both very attractive in a certain sense. The elegant

02:27.040 --> 02:35.200
vampire and the stately, intricate, gorgeous steamboat. But they also have dark
sides, too, of course.

02:45.280 --> 02:53.500
In Fevre Dream, the protagonist, Captain Abner Marsh, owner of a failing
steamboat company, the Fevre River Packet Line, realizes his lifelong dream of

02:53.500 --> 03:01.260
captaining a fast, luxurious steamboat when he becomes partners with the
mysterious Joshua York. All Marsh has to do to maintain the partnership and keep

03:01.260 --> 03:09.000
the fancy steamboat is sail up and down the river and avoid questioning York's
somewhat odd habits. But York begins bringing aboard a strange retinue of

03:09.000 --> 03:16.580
acquaintances, all of whom have nocturnal habits. And, of course, Marsh has
difficulty staying his curiosity. As Marsh learns about York and his friends, he

03:16.580 --> 03:25.340
discovers they are vampires. But Martin presents vampires in a manner never seen
in fantasy. He explains them in rational terms. This meant including some of the

03:25.340 --> 03:34.140
legendary characteristics of vampires, but leaving others out. I wanted to have
rationalized vampires. I wanted to have vampires that I thought could actually

03:34.140 --> 03:46.340
exist, that were not based on, you know, vague supernatural legends handed down
over the years. So I had to look at each of the particular beliefs associated

03:46.340 --> 03:56.080
with vampires and see if there is any way that I could justify this in a
rational manner. Now, obviously, something about vampires not coming out during

03:56.080 --> 04:07.020
day, which the vampires in my book, Fevre Dream, do have that characteristic.
Well, that's very easily explainable. It's just they're nocturnal creatures.

04:08.160 --> 04:20.980
Their skin is extremely sensitive to ultraviolet, so they burn very badly if
they're exposed to daylight. So they avoid it. You can justify that easily. But

04:20.980 --> 04:28.540
you look at something, they're not reflected in mirrors. I mean, there's no way
to justify not being reflected in mirrors scientifically. You have to rewrite,

04:28.760 --> 04:37.500
essentially, all the laws governing light and reflection and refraction and so
on. That's strictly a supernatural motif, so I had to get rid of that.

04:39.000 --> 04:46.760
Obviously, considering that the book is about vampires on Mississippi River
steamboats, I had to get rid of the one that said they can't cross running water

04:46.760 --> 04:53.560
as well, since they sail up and down the steamboat all through the book. More on
George Martin's Fevre Dream on our next show.

