06:22.620 --> 06:24.160
And here are your hosts.

06:28.300 --> 06:36.400
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. Science fiction writer George R.R. Martin's
latest novel, Fevre Dream, a science fictional historical horror effort, was

06:36.400 --> 06:43.380
recently published in hardcover by Poseidon Press and distributed by Simon &
Schuster. As we discussed in our last show, the book combines elements of the

06:43.380 --> 06:52.480
vampire legend and a Mark Twain-like presentation of Mississippi riverboat lore.
Joshua York, the partner of Captain Abner Marsh, is a vampire who has managed to

06:52.480 --> 06:59.380
concoct a potion which will alleviate the red thirst. The scourge which visits
the vampires in Martin's novel periodically and drives them into an

06:59.380 --> 07:07.200
uncontrollable state of bloodlust, which can only be satiated by human blood,
preferably that from young, attractive, living humans. The humans, by the way,

07:07.260 --> 07:15.760
are deprecatingly referred to by some of the vampires as cattle. The existence
of the potion is the key to Martin's novel. It gives the vampires a choice. They

07:15.760 --> 07:22.420
can continue feasting on the blood of the cattle, or they can finally quit
terrorizing the human race and drink only the artificial brew. This choice is

07:22.420 --> 07:30.440
another element which separates Martin's vampires from those of traditional
fantasy. I suppose as much as anything else, I mean, the book is about vampires

07:30.440 --> 07:40.000
on Mississippi river steamboats, but in a deeper sense, it's about moral
choices. And one of the things that Joshua York, the vampire, says to Abner,

07:40.280 --> 07:46.280
Abner Marsh, the protagonist, and that Abner later says back to him is, You make
your choices.

08:14.660 --> 08:22.980
It's a real world, but it's a real world kind of a hollow construct. The real
world is made up of greys. I think real people are made up of greys. We don't

08:22.980 --> 08:33.440
have absolute goods, and we don't have absolute evils. The good and evil that we
have, you know, resides in each of us, and it is a matter of moral choice. Damon

08:33.440 --> 08:41.060
Julian is a charismatic elder vampire who rejects the potion. He did make a
choice eons ago, but he also makes the choice in terms of the book at the

08:41.060 --> 08:44.960
banquet when he essentially rejects what Joshua has to offer.

08:48.480 --> 09:02.060
And states his opposition to Joshua with saying, you know, we are born, this is
what we are born to be, masters of humanity, people who take the lives of those

09:02.060 --> 09:14.100
inferior to us. And this is our nature. So he is making a choice there. He's
rejecting Joshua's potion. He's rejecting the freedom from the red thirst that

09:14.100 --> 09:25.580
Joshua offers, and he's accepting what he thinks is of his superior nature.
Martin told us that he found a close parallel between Julian's view of the human

09:25.580 --> 09:36.080
race and slavery as it existed in the South at the time of the book, 1857. Of
course, there's also certain, you know, resonances there with the whole slavery

09:36.080 --> 09:47.640
thing, which I tried to put through all the way through the book. It takes place
in the antebellum South, late antebellum South, and slavery issue, of course, is

09:47.640 --> 09:59.140
very hot then. And the whole master-slave thing that existed between blacks and
whites in the South then has a kind of fantasy reflection in relations between

09:59.140 --> 10:10.840
vampires. And human beings. This parallel even strikes Abner Marsh as the story
progresses. Abner Marsh is never an evil man. I think by nature he is a good

10:10.840 --> 10:21.920
man. But he is a man at the beginning of the book who is essentially just living
his own life. And the great moral issues of his time, like slavery, are, you

10:21.920 --> 10:28.340
know, things he kind of hashes out over the dinner table but never has any great
personal involvement in.

10:31.480 --> 10:39.960
But as a result of the whole experience with the steamer Fevre Dream and the
things that happen to him, I think Marsh changes and becomes, in essence, a man

10:39.960 --> 10:46.200
who is much more aware of the necessity to make moral choices. More on George
Martin's Fevre Dream on our next show.

