12:15.020 --> 12:16.720
And here are your hosts.

12:20.920 --> 12:29.180
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Science Fiction author George R.R. Martin's
latest novel is Fevre Dream, a science fictional historical horror story about

12:29.180 --> 12:37.640
vampires in Mississippi river boats. Here Martin explains the title of the book.
The title of the book is taken from the name of the steamboat in the book. The

12:37.640 --> 12:45.080
Fevre Dream is named the steamboat. And the reason Abner Marsh names the
steamboat the Fevre Dream is because it is the boat he has always dreamed of

12:45.080 --> 12:55.360
having, the grand, luxurious, fast steamer. And because he is the president, his
company is called Fevre River Package Company, with that odd spelling, the R-E

12:55.360 --> 13:05.600
inverted. Okay, that explains the origin of Fevre Dream. But where did the oddly
spelled fevre originate? It has to do with Captain Marsh's birthplace. He was

13:05.600 --> 13:18.820
born in Galena, Illinois. And the river Galena is located on a small tributary
that comes off the Mississippi, which originally was named the Fevre River, F-E

13:18.820 --> 13:31.140
-V-R-E River, in the early 1800s. And Marsh, of course, was born during that
period and grew up calling it. And in point of fact, and this is all

13:31.140 --> 13:41.780
historically true, the name of that river was changed to the Galena River fairly
early on because, you know, the town got respectable and they didn't want people

13:41.780 --> 13:49.580
thinking they were all sick there. So they thought it would be better to call it
the Galena River. But Galena was a very important steamboat town. And the Fevre

13:49.580 --> 13:58.720
in its early days, today it's nothing but a creek. It's completely silted up and
I've visited it and you couldn't get a rowboat up it, let alone a major steamer.

13:59.060 --> 14:11.280
But in the early 1800s, Galena was a major steamboat port. And the Fevre, or the
Galena River, as it later became, was a very bustling little tributary indeed.

14:12.000 --> 14:20.380
We asked Martin if there were actual steamboats as fast and as luxurious as the
Fevre Dream. The dimensions of the Fevre Dream and the capacity of her engines

14:20.380 --> 14:31.060
and so forth are modeled very closely on the Eclipse. In terms of the book, the
Eclipse is the queen of the river, the fastest, largest, and most luxurious

14:31.060 --> 14:41.000
boat. And it's the one Abner Marsh aspires to displace as fastest steamer on the
river, and that's why he built the Fevre Dream. The Eclipse was a real

14:41.000 --> 14:54.640
historical boat of its era, the 1850s, and was considered the fastest boat of
that era. It did indeed win a very famous steamboat race against the Shotwell.

14:57.080 --> 15:07.760
And some people, including Mark Twain, put forward evidence that the Fevre Dream
was in fact the fastest steamer ever on the river. And there were later steamers

15:07.760 --> 15:19.000
in the 1870s and the 1880s that, while they were not perhaps as fast as the
Fevre Dream in the book or the Eclipse in real life, were even more luxurious,

15:19.360 --> 15:33.380
like the J.M. White, a very fast and incredibly luxurious steamer of the 1870s,
1880s. One of the interesting facts that strikes the reader is that riverboats

15:33.380 --> 15:43.220
were extremely short-lived. That was one of the interesting things that turned
up when I was researching it that kind of startled me, too. I mean, they're such

15:43.220 --> 15:59.320
formidable-looking structures. You'd think they'd be around for ages. But, in
fact, they had a shorter lifespan than the modern car. Martin had to do

15:59.320 --> 16:08.280
considerable research on steamboats to ensure the accuracy of the historical
details in Fevre Dream. It took me two years to do Fevre Dream altogether. The

16:08.280 --> 16:18.320
first year of that was largely research. So a lot of research did go into it,
yes. I think that's a necessity if you're going to do justice to any sort of

16:18.320 --> 16:30.240
historical fiction. Fevre Dream, of course, is historical horror, but I still
think you owe your readers that debt of accuracy insofar as you're capable of

16:30.240 --> 16:32.860
it. More with George Martin on our next show.

