17:55.400 --> 18:00.660
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

18:03.380 --> 18:05.000
And here are your hosts.

18:09.060 --> 18:16.800
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. One of the most popular genres in mass
market literature is the horror genre. We asked science fiction author George R

18:16.800 --> 18:25.400
.R. Martin, author of the recently published horror novel Fevre Dream, why he
thinks the horror genre is currently so successful. I think people may be going

18:25.400 --> 18:38.900
to horror because it's... In horror novels, we're scared, yeah, but we can kind
of control the scares. And, you know, we can read the book and scare ourselves.

18:39.960 --> 18:46.220
But then we put down the book and we know that what we're afraid of, vampires,
werewolves, haunted hotels, whatever,

18:49.200 --> 19:01.620
is not real. And people don't mind dealing with that and kind of getting a
little catharsis out of that. But they don't want to deal with real, the real

19:01.620 --> 19:14.080
terrifying things, violence in the streets and crime and crazed psychos out
there and the threat of nuclear holocaust and all of the other more real fears

19:14.080 --> 19:22.100
that also hang over us. So I think that may be part of it. There are many
creatures that embody horror in the literature. Ghosts, monsters, ghouls,

19:22.180 --> 19:29.040
werewolves, witches. But probably the most enduring image of horror is the
vampire, the nocturnal stalker who drinks the blood of its unwary victims. The

19:29.040 --> 19:38.280
vampire legend spans many cultures. Here Martin tells us about the vampire
legend and the reasons why the legend may be so popular even now. Vampires are

19:38.280 --> 19:48.800
an almost universal legend, which is one thing that turned out when I was
researching Fevre Dream. The vampires we're familiar with, of course, Dracula

19:48.800 --> 20:00.100
and his kin, so to speak, and all the books that are derived from that tradition
are essentially retreads of Eastern European, Romanian, Hungarian, largely

20:00.100 --> 20:10.860
vampire legends. But if you look around the world, you'll find vampire legends
everywhere. In China, in Africa, in the South Seas, there are variants of the

20:10.860 --> 20:23.760
vampire legend. The details differ. But the basic vision of a nocturnal predator
that preys on human beings is present in all of these. And so that would lead

20:23.760 --> 20:36.480
you to wonder why do they have this universal appeal. The easy answer as to why
they're appealing in our culture today, in modern American mass society, I

20:36.480 --> 20:50.800
think, is the sexual nature of the vampire, the sexual symbolism embodied in
Dracula and in the way it's been treated by Hollywood sense, the symbolism of

20:50.800 --> 20:52.140
vampire as seductor,

20:59.700 --> 21:12.360
appeals to something within us and gives legend a lot more resonances than, say,
the werewolf legend or zombies or some of the other things that have never

21:12.360 --> 21:24.520
really achieved the popularity of the vampire legend. But then you could say,
well, that's true for us, but it doesn't explain why the legend is so universal

21:24.520 --> 21:27.940
around the world. And indeed it doesn't, and I don't have an answer for that.

21:45.520 --> 21:53.640
Martin tells us here how he incorporated this universal, transcultural concept
of the vampire in Fevre Dream. In terms of Fevre Dream, I looked at that

21:53.640 --> 22:02.340
universality and I made it one of the bases when I started writing the novel. I
said, what if the reason that these legends are universal is because they're all

22:02.340 --> 22:15.920
remembering the same thing? They're all remembering some kind of racial memory
of a real man-like predatory animal, blood drinker, that is somehow the basis

22:15.920 --> 22:20.040
for all the vampire legends. And that was the premise that I, of course, used in
Fevre Dream.

